Draghi (on Libor): The unspeakable personal behaviour and design flaws have shown once again a faulty governance of the process.
Draghi: The euro is irrevocable.
Draghi: One must remember that with globalisation, it is precisely by sharing sovereignty that countries can better preserve it.
Draghi: We also need to look at the markets for products and services and liberalise where necessary to increase competitiveness.
Draghi: The Summit was a success. For the first time, it seems to me, a clear message was given: exit the crisis with more Europe.
Draghi: We are very open. We do not have any taboos.

Coeuré: It must be ensured that if sovereignty is elevated to the EU level, so is democratic control.
Coeuré: The euro area is moving towards a more sustainable equilibrium, and comparably fast in international comparison
Coeuré: Right response to discrepancy between fundamentals and perceptions is not defeatism but to fix the inst. flaws that facilitate it.
Coeuré: EA deficit 2012: 3%, US: 8%, Japan: 10%.  EA debt 2012: 90%, US: 106%, Japan: 235%.
Coeuré: In the aggregate, euro area enjoys better fundamentals than U.S. or Japan, and yet it is viewed as a more risky place to invest.
Coeuré: In those countries experiencing severe sovereign debt tensions, fiscal consolidation is unavoidable to maintain market access
Coeuré: For the longer-term, sound fiscal policies are essential to lower borrowing costs and encourage investment.
Coeuré: Against that background, what has been achieved (EFSF, ESM, "Six-Pack”, Fiscal Compact) is already very significant.
Coeuré: Euro area has existed for just 13 years and strengthening of its institutions began only two years ago
Coeuré: U.S. had 200 years to create inst. to run a vast and diverse econ. area and still sometimes struggles with difficult decisions.
Coeuré: One needs an appr. sense of perspective.Unrealistic to expect the euro area to have reaction-function of  nation-state like the U.S.
